CHARTA IUDICIORUM LATINORUM CONSTANTINOPOLITANORUM
CHARTER OF THE LATIN COURTS OF CONSTANTINOPLE

Establishing Jurisdiction, Procedure, and Enforcement for Disputes Among the Latin Nations and Between Latin and Greek Subjects

Drafted at Constantinople, in the Palace of Blachernae
The 15th day of April, in the Year of Our Lord 1434

PREAMBLE

Whereas the City of Constantinople, Queen of Cities, has since ancient times been a meeting place of nations, where merchants of diverse lands conduct commerce under the protection of the Roman Emperor;

And whereas disputes arising between persons of different nations have heretofore been resolved through negotiation between quarters, or not resolved at all, leading to violence, bloodshed, and the disruption of trade;

And whereas justice delayed is justice denied, and justice partial is no justice at all;

And whereas all Christian peoples share a common heritage of law descending from Rome, through both the secular codes of Justinian and the customs of merchants developed in the great trading ports of Christendom;

Now therefore, we who subscribe our names do hereby establish this Charter for the governance of disputes among the Latin nations present in Constantinople, and between Latin and Greek subjects, to the end that justice may be done swiftly, impartially, and in accordance with law.

TITLE I: JURISDICTION

Article 1: Scope of Authority

§1. The Courts established by this Charter shall have jurisdiction over:

(a) All commercial disputes arising between merchants, traders, factors, or agents of different nations conducting business within the walls of Constantinople or its harbor;

(b) All criminal matters arising between subjects of different nations within the walls of Constantinople or its harbor;

(c) All civil matters—including but not limited to property disputes, inheritance claims, contracts, and torts—arising between subjects of different nations within the walls of Constantinople or its harbor;

(d) Such other matters as the parties may voluntarily submit to the Court's jurisdiction by mutual written agreement.

§2. The Courts shall NOT have jurisdiction over:

(a) Matters purely internal to a single nation's quarter, where all parties are subjects of that nation and the dispute arose entirely within that quarter;

(b) Matters of faith, doctrine, or ecclesiastical discipline, which remain the province of the respective churches;

(c) Matters touching the sovereign authority of the Emperor, which remain the province of the Imperial courts;

(d) Disputes already resolved by final judgment of a competent court, unless new evidence of fraud or perjury emerges.

§3. Where jurisdiction is disputed, the Court shall hear argument from both parties and render a preliminary judgment on its own competence before proceeding to the merits.

Article 2: Standing

§1. Any person, regardless of nation or station, may bring a matter before the Court, provided:

(a) The person has suffered injury, or represents one who has suffered injury, or acts in official capacity on behalf of a nation or community;

(b) The matter falls within the Court's jurisdiction as defined above;

(c) The person submits to the Court's authority and agrees to abide by its judgment.

§2. In criminal matters, accusation may be brought by:

(a) The injured party, or their heirs or legal representatives;

(b) An official representative of the injured party's nation (podestà, bailo, consul, or equivalent);

(c) Any witness to the crime, acting in the public interest;

(d) An officer of the Court itself, where the crime is notorious and no private accuser comes forward.

§3. The accuser in a criminal matter bears the burden of proof. Should the accusation fail for want of evidence, the accuser shall not face penalty unless the Court finds the accusation was brought maliciously and without reasonable foundation.

Article 3: Territorial Extent

§1. The Court's authority extends throughout the City of Constantinople, including:

(a) All quarters, whether Latin, Greek, or mixed;

(b) The harbors, docks, and anchorages of the Golden Horn and the Sea of Marmara within sight of the city walls;

(c) Vessels at anchor or moored within said harbors, regardless of the flag they fly.

§2. The Court may hear matters arising outside these boundaries if all parties consent to its jurisdiction and the subject matter has substantial connection to Constantinople.

TITLE II: APPLICABLE LAW

Article 4: Commercial Matters

§1. In all commercial disputes—including but not limited to contracts, debts, partnerships, bills of exchange, insurance, shipping, and the quality of goods—the Court shall apply the lex mercatoria, the customary law of merchants recognized throughout Christendom.

§2. The fundamental principles of the lex mercatoria include:

(a) **Good Faith (Bona Fides): All parties to commercial dealings are bound to act honestly and without deception. Fraud, misrepresentation, adulteration of goods, use of false weights or measures, and similar deceits are offenses against the entire merchant community.

(b) Sanctity of Contract (Pacta Sunt Servanda): Agreements freely made shall be honored. A promise given binds the promisor. Written contracts take precedence over verbal understandings where the two conflict.

(c) Fair Dealing: Prices must be agreed, not imposed. Quality must be as represented. Goods delivered must match goods promised.

(d) Prompt Resolution: Commercial justice must be swift. The Court shall endeavor to resolve commercial disputes within fourteen days of the matter being brought, except where complexity requires additional time.

§3.** Where the lex mercatoria is silent or unclear, the Court may look to:

(a) The commercial customs of the parties' home nations;

(b) The established practices of the Constantinople trading community;

(c) Reason and equity.

Article 5: Criminal Matters

§1. In all criminal matters—including but not limited to murder, assault, theft, arson, rape, and other offenses against person or property—the Court shall apply the criminal procedure and substantive law of the Basilika, the Byzantine codification of Roman law.

§2. The fundamental principles of Byzantine criminal procedure include:

(a) The Right to Hear the Accusation: No person shall be tried without being informed of the specific charges against them;

(b) The Right to Respond: The accused shall have opportunity to speak in their own defense and to present evidence and witnesses on their behalf;

(c) The Right to Confront Witnesses: The accused may question those who testify against them, either directly or through an advocate;

(d) The Burden of Proof: The accuser must prove guilt; the accused need not prove innocence;

(e) Standards of Evidence: Guilt in capital cases requires either confession freely given (not extracted under torture) or the testimony of at least two credible witnesses with direct knowledge of the act, or such weight of circumstantial evidence as leaves no reasonable doubt.

§3. The following acts are recognized as capital crimes warranting death:

(a) Murder—the unlawful killing of another person with intent;

(b) Treason—betrayal of the city or its lawful authorities to enemies;

(c) Arson—the deliberate setting of fires that endanger life;

(d) Rape—carnal violation by force;

(e) Kidnapping for ransom or sale into slavery.

§4. Lesser crimes—including theft, assault not resulting in death, fraud, and similar offenses—shall be punished according to the severity of the act and the circumstances, with penalties ranging from fines to imprisonment to banishment to corporal punishment, as the Court determines just.

Article 6: Civil Matters

§1. In civil matters not of a commercial character—including property disputes, inheritance, marriage contracts, and personal injury—the Court shall apply the principles of Roman civil law as preserved in the Basilika.

§2. Where Roman law conflicts with the established custom of one party's nation on matters of family law or inheritance, the Court shall endeavor to find an equitable resolution that respects both legal traditions.

TITLE III: COMPOSITION OF THE COURT

Article 7: The Panel of Judges

§1. Each nation maintaining a recognized quarter or commercial presence in Constantinople shall nominate one qualified jurist to serve on the Panel of Judges. Qualifications include:

(a) Knowledge of the lex mercatoria and basic principles of Roman law;

(b) Good reputation and no conviction for dishonesty or violence;

(c) Residence in Constantinople for the duration of service;

(d) No current dispute pending before the Court.

§2. Nominated judges shall be confirmed by agreement of the existing Panel, or in the absence of an existing Panel, by the subscribing parties to this Charter.

§3. Judges shall serve for a term of two years, renewable without limit. A judge may be removed for cause—including corruption, incapacity, or abandonment of duty—by unanimous vote of the remaining judges.

Article 8: Selection of Judges for Individual Cases

§1. The principle of impartiality requires that no judge shall hear a case involving their own nation as a party.

§2. For disputes between two nations: The judge or judges shall be drawn from a third nation or nations not party to the dispute.

§3. For disputes involving three or more nations: Judges shall be drawn from nations not party to the dispute. If insufficient neutral judges exist, the parties shall agree on a selection, or lots shall be drawn.

§4. For disputes between a Latin party and a Greek party: The judge or judges shall be drawn from Latin nations not involved, unless the Greek party requests and the Latin party agrees to include a Byzantine jurist familiar with the Basilika.

§5. For complex matters or capital cases: The Court may sit as a panel of three judges rather than one, drawn according to the principles above.

§6. Any party may challenge a proposed judge for cause—including personal enmity, financial interest, or prior involvement in the matter. Challenges shall be heard by the remaining judges, whose decision is final.

Article 9: The Presiding Authority

§1. Until such time as the subscribing nations establish a permanent rotating presidency, the authority to convene the Court, assign judges, and enforce judgments shall rest with the guarantor of this Charter.

§2. The Presiding Authority may hear cases personally, particularly in matters of first impression or exceptional importance, sitting as sole judge or as head of a panel.

§3. The Presiding Authority shall not hear cases in which their own nation is a party, except by unanimous consent of all parties.

TITLE IV: PROCEDURE

Article 10: Initiating a Case

§1. A matter is brought before the Court by filing a written complaint (libellus) with the Presiding Authority or designated clerk, setting forth:

(a) The names and nations of the parties;

(b) The nature of the dispute or accusation;

(c) The relief or penalty sought;

(d) A summary of the evidence to be presented.

§2. Upon receipt of the complaint, the Court shall:

(a) Determine whether the matter falls within its jurisdiction;

(b) If so, summon the opposing party to respond within three days for commercial matters, seven days for civil matters, and immediately for criminal matters where the accused is in custody;

(c) Assign a judge or panel according to the rules above.

Article 11: The Response

§1. The responding party shall file a written answer (responsio) admitting or denying the allegations and setting forth any defenses or counterclaims.

§2. Failure to respond within the allotted time may result in default judgment against the non-responding party, unless good cause for delay is shown.

Article 12: The Hearing

§1. The hearing shall proceed as follows:

(a) The accuser or complainant presents their case first, calling witnesses and presenting documents;

(b) The responding party may question each witness after their testimony;

(c) The responding party then presents their defense, calling witnesses and presenting documents;

(d) The accuser may question each defense witness;

(e) Both parties may make closing arguments summarizing their positions;

(f) The judge or panel retires to deliberate.

§2. All testimony shall be given under oath, with the witness acknowledging that perjury is a sin before God and a crime punishable by the Court.

§3. The judge may question witnesses directly at any point to clarify matters of fact.

§4. The hearing shall be conducted in a language understood by all parties, with interpreters provided as necessary.

Article 13: Evidence

§1. The following forms of evidence are recognized, in descending order of weight:

(a) Confession: A free and voluntary admission of the facts by a party. Confessions obtained through torture or threat are inadmissible.

(b) Documents: Written contracts, letters, account books, and official records bearing authentic seals or signatures.

(c) Eyewitness Testimony: Statements by persons with direct knowledge of the relevant facts, given under oath.

(d) Expert Testimony: Opinions of persons with specialized knowledge (e.g., physicians on cause of death, merchants on customary trade practices).

(e) Circumstantial Evidence: Facts from which the relevant events may be inferred (e.g., motive, opportunity, possession of stolen goods).

(f) Character Evidence: Testimony regarding a party's reputation for honesty or dishonesty, admitted only where directly relevant.

§2. The judge shall weigh all evidence according to its credibility and relevance, giving more weight to disinterested witnesses than to parties or their close associates.

§3. In capital cases, conviction requires proof beyond reasonable doubt. In civil and commercial cases, the preponderance of credible evidence suffices.

Article 14: Judgment

§1. The judge or panel shall render judgment within seven days of the close of evidence, except in cases of unusual complexity.

§2. Every judgment shall include:

(a) A statement of the facts as found by the Court;

(b) The legal principles applied;

(c) The reasoning connecting facts to law;

(d) The verdict and, where applicable, the penalty or remedy imposed.

§3. Judgments shall be recorded in writing, with copies provided to all parties and preserved in the Court's archives.

TITLE V: PENALTIES AND REMEDIES

Article 15: Criminal Penalties

§1. The Court may impose the following penalties for criminal offenses:

(a) Death: By hanging, for capital crimes proven beyond reasonable doubt;

(b) Mutilation: Loss of hand for theft, branding for fraud, as appropriate to the offense and local custom;

(c) Imprisonment: For terms proportionate to the offense;

(d) Banishment: Permanent or temporary expulsion from Constantinople;

(e) Corporal Punishment: Flogging, for lesser offenses;

(f) Fines: Monetary penalties payable to the victim, their heirs, or the public treasury.

§2. Penalties may be combined as justice requires.

§3. Execution of death sentences shall be carried out by officers of the Presiding Authority, in public, within seven days of judgment unless appeal is pending.

Article 16: Civil and Commercial Remedies

§1. The Court may order the following remedies in civil and commercial cases:

(a) Monetary Damages: Compensation for losses suffered;

(b) Specific Performance: Ordering a party to fulfill their contractual obligations;

(c) Rescission: Declaring a contract void and ordering return of consideration;

(d) Injunction: Ordering a party to cease harmful conduct;

(e) Restitution: Ordering return of property wrongfully taken or held.

§2. Interest may be awarded on monetary judgments at a rate not exceeding eight percent per annum.

TITLE VI: APPEAL

Article 17: Right of Appeal

§1. Any party aggrieved by a judgment may appeal within fourteen days of the judgment being rendered.

§2. Appeals must be in writing and must specify:

(a) The grounds for appeal (error of law, error of fact, new evidence, or procedural irregularity);

(b) The relief sought.

§3. Appeals shall be heard by a panel of three judges, none of whom sat on the original case and none of whom are of the same nation as the appellant.

Article 18: Scope of Review

§1. On appeal, the panel may:

(a) Affirm the judgment below;

(b) Reverse the judgment in whole or in part;

(c) Modify the penalty or remedy;

(d) Remand for new trial where procedural errors tainted the original proceeding.

§2. New evidence may be considered on appeal only if it was not available at the original trial despite reasonable diligence.

§3. Execution of judgment is stayed pending appeal, except that accused persons may remain in custody if flight risk exists.

Article 19: Finality

§1. The decision of the appellate panel is final. No further appeal lies except to the Presiding Authority on grounds of manifest injustice or corruption, and such extraordinary review is discretionary.

TITLE VII: ENFORCEMENT

Article 20: Compliance

§1. All parties who submit to the Court's jurisdiction are bound to comply with its judgments.

§2. Subscribing nations pledge to enforce judgments against their own subjects, including:

(a) Collection of fines and damages;

(b) Surrender of persons for imprisonment or execution;

(c) Recognition and enforcement of the Court's orders within their quarters.

Article 21: Non-Compliance

§1. If a party fails to comply with a judgment:

(a) The Court shall issue a writ of non-compliance, publicly recorded;

(b) The non-compliant party shall be barred from bringing any matter before the Court until compliance is achieved;

(c) The Court may authorize seizure of the non-compliant party's goods or property within its jurisdiction;

(d) The Presiding Authority may direct armed force to effect compliance.

§2. If a nation or quarter shelters a person subject to the Court's judgment, refusing surrender or extradition:

(a) The Court shall issue formal demand to the authorities of that nation or quarter;

(b) If the demand is not satisfied within fourteen days, the sheltering nation or quarter shall be deemed in contempt;

(c) Contempt may be punished by exclusion of that nation's subjects from the Court's protection, suspension of commercial privileges, or such other sanctions as the Presiding Authority deems appropriate;

(d) Persistent contempt may be reported to the sovereign authorities of the offending nation for action.

Article 22: Extradition

§1. When a person subject to the Court's jurisdiction flees to territory outside Constantinople, the Court may issue a request for extradition to the relevant sovereign authority.

§2. Subscribing nations pledge to honor such requests in good faith, subject to their own laws regarding extradition.

§3. Pending extradition, judgment is not void but held in abeyance, and the fugitive status is recorded in the Court's archives and published to all subscribing nations.

TITLE VIII: ADMINISTRATION

Article 23: Records

§1. The Court shall maintain archives including:

(a) All complaints and responses filed;

(b) Records of proceedings, including witness lists and summaries of testimony;

(c) All judgments rendered, with full reasoning;

(d) Records of compliance and non-compliance.

§2. These archives shall be open to inspection by parties to concluded cases and by officials of subscribing nations.

Article 24: Funding

§1. The Court shall be funded by:

(a) Filing fees paid by parties initiating cases;

(b) Fines collected;

(c) Contributions from subscribing nations in proportion to their commercial presence.

§2. Judges shall receive reasonable compensation for their service, funded from the Court's treasury.

Article 25: Amendments

§1. This Charter may be amended by agreement of all subscribing nations.

§2. Proposed amendments shall be circulated to all subscribers with at least thirty days for consideration before adoption.

TITLE IX: RATIFICATION AND EFFECT

Article 26: Subscription

§1. This Charter takes effect upon subscription by at least two nations maintaining commercial presence in Constantinople, plus the endorsement of the Presiding Authority.

§2. Additional nations may subscribe at any time by filing written acceptance with the Court's archives.

§3. Subscription by the Imperial authority of Constantinople, when obtained, shall extend the Court's jurisdiction to matters between Latin and Greek subjects as described herein.

Article 27: Withdrawal

§1. Any subscribing nation may withdraw from this Charter upon sixty days' written notice.

§2. Withdrawal does not affect judgments already rendered or proceedings already commenced.

§3. A withdrawn nation's subjects may still bring matters before the Court but may not serve as judges.

CONCLUSIO

This Charter is established in the hope that justice, administered fairly and without favor, may bring peace where there has been strife, and order where there has been chaos. Let all who subscribe commit themselves to its principles, and let all who come before it receive judgment according to law.

Drafted at Constantinople this fifteenth day of April, in the Year of Our Lord 1434, in the presence of the undersigned.

