TAKTIKON OF ROMANIA

A Charter Establishing Military Obligations for the Defense and Restoration of the Roman Empire

Drafted at Constantinople, in the Palace of Blachernae
The 15th day of April, in the Year of Our Lord 1434

PREAMBLE

Whereas the Roman Empire, guardian of Christian civilization for eleven centuries, now faces extinction at the hands of the Ottoman Turks;

And whereas the ancient systems of military obligation that once made the Empire unconquerable have fallen into decay through neglect, corruption, and the loss of territories that sustained them;

And whereas the defense of Constantinople and the restoration of Roman lands require not merely courage but organization, not merely faith but structure;

And whereas divine providence has raised up a Defender for the Roman people in their hour of greatest need;

Now therefore, this Charter establishes the military obligations of all subjects and the authority of the Defensor Romaniae to command, organize, and lead the forces necessary for the Empire's salvation.

TITLE I: THE DEFENSOR ROMANIAE

Article 1: Creation of the Office

§1. There is hereby established the office of Defensor Romaniae—Defender of Romania—to be held by His Most Christian Majesty Juan II, King of Castile, León, Toledo, Galicia, Seville, Córdoba, Murcia, Jaén, the Algarve, Algeciras, and Gibraltar, Lord of Vizcaya and Molina, Conqueror of Granada.

§2. This office is created in recognition that God, in His providence, has sent a champion to defend His people when their own strength has failed. It carries no claim to the Imperial throne, no authority over matters of Orthodox faith and doctrine, and no diminution of the Emperor's sacred dignity as isapostolos and rightful sovereign of the Roman realm.

§3. The Defensor Romaniae serves as guardian and protector of the Roman people until such time as the Empire can stand secure upon its own foundations, at which time this office shall be dissolved or transformed according to the wisdom of Emperor and Defender together.

Article 2: Military Authority

§1. The Defensor Romaniae holds supreme command over all military forces operating in defense of Constantinople and for the restoration of Roman lands, including:

(a) All armies raised under this Charter, whether professional, thematic, or militia;

(b) All naval forces, whether imperial, allied, or contributed by subscribing nations;

(c) All foreign auxiliaries, mercenaries, and allied contingents serving the cause of restoration;

(d) All garrison forces in Constantinople and in territories reconquered under this Charter.

§2. The Defensor Romaniae may:

(a) Summon all persons owing military obligation to service;

(b) Appoint and dismiss military officers at all ranks;

(c) Determine strategy, direct campaigns, and order the movement of forces;

(d) Establish military regulations, discipline, and standards of training;

(e) Requisition supplies, transport, and materials necessary for military operations;

(f) Negotiate with enemies concerning truces, prisoner exchanges, and terms of surrender;

(g) Distribute conquered territories according to the systems established in this Charter.

§3. The Emperor retains:

(a) The sacred authority to bless armies and consecrate banners;

(b) The right to be consulted on matters of grand strategy;

(c) The dignity of ultimate sovereignty, in whose name victories are proclaimed;

(d) The authority to dissolve this Charter by mutual agreement with the Defensor.

Article 3: Civil Authority

§1. In matters touching military necessity, the Defensor Romaniae may:

(a) Requisition materials and labor for fortification construction and repair;

(b) Impose curfews and movement restrictions during military emergencies;

(c) Commandeer vessels, wagons, and animals for military transport;

(d) Establish military courts for offenses committed by persons under arms.

§2. Civil governance in Constantinople remains under Imperial authority. The Defensor Romaniae does not:

(a) Collect taxes, except those specifically designated for military purposes under this Charter;

(b) Administer justice in non-military matters, except as provided in the Charter of the Latin Courts;

(c) Appoint civil officials or interfere in civil administration;

(d) Legislate on matters unrelated to defense and military organization.

§3. In reconquered territories, civil and military authority shall be exercised jointly until permanent administration is established, with the Defensor holding precedence in matters affecting security.

TITLE II: THE URBAN MILITIA

Article 4: Universal Obligation

§1. Every able-bodied male resident of Constantinople between the ages of sixteen and fifty-five owes service in the Urban Militia, without exception of rank, wealth, or nation.

§2. "Able-bodied" means capable of bearing arms and performing military duty. Exemptions for physical incapacity shall be certified by examination and recorded in the militia rolls.

§3. The only exemptions from militia service are:

(a) Clergy in holy orders, who serve as chaplains and healers rather than combatants;

(b) Physicians and surgeons, who serve in medical capacity;

(c) Those already serving in professional military forces or thematic obligations.

§4. No exemption may be purchased. No substitutes may be hired. The obligation is personal and non-transferable.

Article 5: Organization by Guild and Quarter

§1. The Urban Militia shall be organized according to the traditional guild and quarter structure of Constantinople:

(a) Each recognized guild shall maintain a militia company (tagma) comprising all members and journeymen of military age;

(b) Each quarter shall maintain militia units comprising residents not enrolled in guild companies;

(c) The Latin quarters shall maintain separate units under their own officers, coordinated with the Greek militia structure.

§2. Guild Masters and Quarter Captains are responsible for:

(a) Maintaining accurate rolls of all persons owing militia service;

(b) Ensuring attendance at prescribed training sessions;

(c) Reporting absences and exemption claims to militia authorities;

(d) Storing and maintaining guild or quarter armaments.

§3. Failure to maintain accurate rolls or enforce attendance shall result in fines against the responsible guild or quarter, collectible from guild treasuries or quarter assessments.

Article 6: Training Requirements

§1. All militia members shall attend mandatory training as follows:

(a) Basic Training: Upon enrollment, forty consecutive days of intensive drill in weapons handling, formation fighting, and wall defense;

(b) Ongoing Training: One full day every seven days (the Day of Mars), devoted to drill and exercises;

(c) Seasonal Exercises: Four times yearly, three consecutive days of large-scale maneuvers combining multiple units.

§2. Training shall be conducted by professional officers appointed by the Defensor Romaniae, assisted by veterans and experienced militia leaders.

§3. Training shall include:

(a) Individual weapons proficiency—spear, sword, bow, crossbow as appropriate to assignment;

(b) Formation drill—shield walls, pike squares, organized advance and retreat;

(c) Wall defense—manning positions, responding to signals, coordinating with adjacent units;

(d) Basic fortification—digging, construction, repair of defensive works;

(e) Fire response—controlling blazes, preventing spread during siege conditions.

§4. Absence from training without valid cause (illness, family emergency, essential civic duty) shall be punished by:

(a) First offense: Fine of one day's wages;

(b) Second offense: Fine of one week's wages;

(c) Third offense: Public labor on fortifications for fourteen days;

(d) Persistent absence: Imprisonment and forfeiture of property.

Article 7: Equipment

§1. The Defensor Romaniae shall provide initial equipment to all militia members from the Imperial arsenals and from contributions under the Apokatastasis, including:

(a) Primary weapon appropriate to assignment (spear, pike, sword, bow, or crossbow);

(b) Secondary weapon (short sword or dagger);

(c) Helmet of leather or iron;

(d) Shield appropriate to assignment;

(e) Padded jacket or gambeson.

§2. Equipment issued remains the property of the militia stores. Members are responsible for maintenance and must return equipment upon death, disability, or departure from the city.

§3. Members who acquire personal equipment of superior quality may use it in place of issued equipment, subject to inspection for adequacy.

§4. Guilds with traditional association to particular crafts shall contribute to equipment production:

(a) Smiths' guilds: Weapons and armor repair, production of arrowheads and spear points;

(b) Leather workers: Armor padding, scabbards, belts, and straps;

(c) Carpenters: Spear shafts, shield construction, siege equipment;

(d) Rope makers: Bowstrings, siege cordage, naval supplies.

Such contributions shall be compensated at fair rates from military funds.

Article 8: Wall Assignments

§1. Every militia unit shall be assigned a specific section of the Theodosian Walls or sea walls for defense. Assignments shall be recorded and posted publicly.

§2. Upon the sounding of the alarm—bells, trumpets, or beacon fires—every militia member shall proceed immediately to their assigned position, equipped and ready for combat.

§3. Response time from alarm to full manning of walls shall not exceed two hours. Units shall drill this response regularly.

§4. Wall assignments shall be reviewed quarterly and adjusted as population shifts or military necessity requires.

Article 9: Militia in Offensive Operations

§1. The Urban Militia is primarily a defensive force. However, militia units may be called to serve in offensive operations beyond the walls under the following conditions:

(a) The immediate threat to Constantinople has been relieved;

(b) Sufficient forces remain to garrison the walls;

(c) The campaign is of limited duration (not exceeding ninety days);

(d) Service is voluntary for campaigns beyond Thrace.

§2. Militia members who volunteer for offensive campaigns shall receive:

(a) Wages equivalent to professional soldiers for the duration of service;

(b) A share of any plunder according to established military custom;

(c) Priority consideration for land grants in conquered territories.

§3. Distinguished service in offensive operations may qualify militia members for elevation to professional forces or thematic cavalry obligations.

TITLE III: THE PRONOIA OBLIGATIONS

Article 10: Reinstatement of Pronoia Service

§1. All holders of pronoia grants—revenues from lands, villages, harbors, tolls, or other sources granted by imperial authority—owe military service proportional to their grant's value.

§2. This obligation, long neglected, is hereby reinstated and shall be strictly enforced. No pronoia holder may collect revenues without fulfilling military duties.

§3. The scale of obligation shall be:

(a) Minor pronoia (annual revenue below 100 hyperpyra): One equipped infantryman, or personal service as infantry;

(b) Medium pronoia (annual revenue 100-500 hyperpyra): One equipped cavalryman with horse and armor, or personal service as cavalry;

(c) Major pronoia (annual revenue 500-2000 hyperpyra): Three equipped cavalrymen, or personal service plus two additional mounted men;

(d) Great pronoia (annual revenue above 2000 hyperpyra): One cavalryman per 500 hyperpyra of revenue, with personal service required of the holder unless aged or infirm.

§4. "Equipped" means armed and armored to standards prescribed by military regulations, mounted on horses fit for campaign service, with supplies sufficient for thirty days in the field.

Article 11: Registration and Inspection

§1. Within sixty days of this Charter's ratification, all pronoia holders shall register their grants with the military authority, declaring:

(a) The source and nature of the grant;

(b) The assessed annual revenue;

(c) The military obligation thereby incurred;

(d) The names and equipment of men provided, or declaration of personal service.

§2. Annual inspections shall verify that:

(a) Declared revenues are accurate;

(b) Required men are available and equipped;

(c) Horses are fit for service;

(d) Equipment meets prescribed standards.

§3. False declaration of revenues shall be punished by:

(a) Fine equal to twice the undeclared amount;

(b) Forfeiture of the pronoia for persistent fraud.

§4. Failure to provide required men or equipment shall be punished by:

(a) Fine sufficient to hire equivalent forces for one year;

(b) Forfeiture of the pronoia for persistent failure.

Article 12: Household Guards

§1. Great nobles maintaining private household guards (oikeioi) shall convert these forces to public service under the following terms:

(a) All household guards shall be registered with military authority;

(b) When summoned, household guards serve under the Defensor's command, not their lord's private direction;

(c) Household guards count toward the lord's pronoia obligation if properly equipped and trained;

(d) Maintenance of guards beyond pronoia obligation is permitted but such excess forces remain subject to summons.

§2. No noble may maintain armed household forces exceeding twice their pronoia obligation without specific authorization from the Defensor Romaniae.

§3. Unauthorized private armies shall be disbanded. Resistance to disbandment constitutes rebellion against lawful military authority.

Article 13: Noble Personal Service

§1. Holders of great pronoia—those with revenues exceeding 2000 hyperpyra annually—owe personal service in campaign unless exempted for age (over sixty) or certified physical incapacity.

§2. Personal service means actual presence in the field, under arms, sharing the dangers and hardships of campaign. Service cannot be fulfilled by remaining in Constantinople while retainers march.

§3. Nobles who evade personal service through feigned illness, invented emergencies, or simple absence shall:

(a) First offense: Forfeit one year's pronoia revenue to military funds;

(b) Second offense: Forfeit the pronoia entirely;

(c) Third offense: Face charges of cowardice before military tribunal.

§4. The principle is absolute: everyone fights. Rank provides no shelter from obligation. Wealth purchases no exemption. The farmer on the walls and the lord in the cavalry owe the same duty to the Empire's defense.

TITLE IV: THE THEMATIC SYSTEM

Article 14: Establishment in Reconquered Territories

§1. As territories are liberated from Ottoman occupation, military land grants shall be established according to the ancient thematic model, adapted to present circumstances.

§2. The purposes of the thematic system are:

(a) To populate reconquered lands with settlers capable of defending them;

(b) To create a self-sustaining military force that does not depend on treasury payments;

(c) To bind families to military service across generations;

(d) To reward those who fight for the restoration with permanent stake in its success.

§3. Land for thematic grants shall come from:

(a) Former Ottoman timar holdings, reverting to Roman sovereignty upon liberation;

(b) Abandoned lands whose former owners cannot be identified;

(c) Lands confiscated from those who actively collaborated with Ottoman rule;

(d) Imperial domain lands designated for military settlement.

Article 15: Categories of Grants

§1. Thematic grants shall be made in three categories:

**Infantry Holdings (Stratiotika Ktemata):**

(a) Sufficient land to support one family and equip one infantryman;

(b) Approximately 30-50 modioi of arable land, depending on soil quality;

(c) Obligation: One equipped infantryman when summoned, attending monthly training;

(d) Granted to: Common soldiers, militiamen who volunteer for settlement, Greek farmers already working the land who accept military obligation.

**Cavalry Holdings (Kaballika Ktemata):**

(a) Sufficient land to support one family, maintain one war horse, and equip one cavalryman;

(b) Approximately 100-150 modioi of arable land, with pasture for horses;

(c) Obligation: One equipped cavalryman with horse when summoned, attending monthly training;

(d) Granted to: Distinguished soldiers, junior officers, existing small landholders who can demonstrate horsemanship.

**Officer Holdings (Archontika Ktemata):**

(a) Larger estates supporting multiple military obligations;

(b) 300+ modioi with associated rights and revenues;

(c) Obligation: Personal service as officer, plus provision of additional men according to holding size;

(d) Granted to: Proven commanders, nobles who demonstrate exceptional service, those entrusted with regional military responsibility.

Article 16: Terms and Conditions

§1. Thematic grants are hereditary but conditional:

(a) The grant passes to heirs so long as military obligation is fulfilled;

(b) Grants may not be sold, donated, or alienated without authorization;

(c) Grants may not be divided below minimum size for their category;

(d) If the line fails or obligation goes unfulfilled for three consecutive summons, the grant reverts to military authority for redistribution.

§2. Holders of thematic grants must:

(a) Reside on or near the granted land;

(b) Maintain prescribed weapons and equipment (provided initially, self-maintained thereafter);

(c) Attend monthly training sessions conducted by regional officers;

(d) Answer summons within prescribed time (generally seven days for local defense, fourteen days for distant campaign);

(e) Serve for the duration of the campaign or until properly discharged.

§3. Holders of thematic grants may not:

(a) Abandon the land for more than one year without authorization;

(b) Convert agricultural land to other uses that reduce its capacity to support military obligation;

(c) Accumulate multiple grants beyond their capacity to fulfill combined obligations;

(d) Transfer obligation to substitutes or hired men (personal service required).

Article 17: Initial Equipment and Training

§1. Recognizing that populations under Ottoman rule have been forbidden weapons for generations, the Defensor Romaniae shall provide:

(a) Initial weapons and equipment to all new thematic grant holders;

(b) Intensive training for the first year following grant—not less than ninety days of professional instruction;

(c) Ongoing training supervision by professional officers assigned to each thematic district;

(d) Gradual transition to self-equipment over a period of ten years.

§2. The cost of initial equipment and training shall be borne by:

(a) Contributions under the Apokatastasis framework;

(b) Revenues from reconquered territories;

(c) The military treasury of the Defensor Romaniae;

(d) Plunder and tribute captured from the enemy.

§3. After the initial ten-year period, thematic holders are responsible for maintaining their own equipment. Failure to maintain adequate equipment shall be punished as failure to fulfill military obligation.

Article 18: Rights and Protections

§1. Thematic grant holders enjoy the following rights:

(a) Security of tenure so long as obligations are fulfilled;

(b) Exemption from ordinary taxation on the granted land (military service substitutes for tax);

(c) The right to pass the grant to heirs;

(d) Access to military justice for disputes arising from service;

(e) Compensation for wounds suffered in service, support for families of those killed.

§2. Widows of fallen soldiers retain the grant for their lifetime or until remarriage, provided a son or other male heir can fulfill military obligation upon reaching age sixteen.

§3. Orphans of fallen soldiers retain the grant under guardianship until reaching military age. Guardians must ensure the orphan receives military training.

§4. Soldiers permanently disabled in service retain their grants without military obligation, in recognition of sacrifice already given.

Article 19: Distribution Principles

§1. In distributing thematic grants, priority shall be given to:

(a) Soldiers who served in the campaign that liberated the territory;

(b) Greek farmers already working the land who accept military obligation and demonstrate loyalty;

(c) Volunteers from Constantinople and other Roman territories willing to resettle;

(d) Veterans of allied forces who wish to remain and serve the Empire.

§2. Distribution shall aim for mixed settlement where practical—newcomers alongside existing populations—to prevent isolation and promote integration.

§3. Greeks who converted to Islam under Ottoman rule may receive grants if they:

(a) Return to Orthodox Christianity (or accept baptism if previously unconverted);

(b) Demonstrate loyalty to the restored Roman authority;

(c) Fulfill all military obligations without exception.

Those unwilling to fulfill these conditions may remain as taxpaying subjects but shall not receive military land grants.

§4. No grants shall be made to:

(a) Active collaborators with Ottoman authority against Roman populations;

(b) Those who voluntarily served in Ottoman military forces;

(c) Those who informed against Christians to Ottoman authorities.

Such persons shall face justice according to the severity of their collaboration.

TITLE V: THE PROFESSIONAL FORCES

Article 20: The Tagmata

§1. At the core of the military structure shall stand the professional tagmata—standing regiments serving year-round for wages, forming the elite force for offensive operations and the backbone of defense.

§2. The tagmata shall comprise:

(a) **Heavy Cavalry (Kataphraktoi): Fully armored horsemen capable of shock combat;

(b) Light Cavalry (Trapezitai): Mobile forces for scouting, screening, and pursuit;

(c) Heavy Infantry (Skutatoi): Armored infantry forming the battle line;

(d) Archers and Crossbowmen (Toxotai): Ranged troops for both field and siege;

(e) Engineers (Mekhanikoi): Specialists in siege craft, fortification, and military construction;

(f) Marines (Nautatoi Stratiotes): Troops trained for naval combat and amphibious operations.

§3. Professional soldiers shall be recruited from:

(a) Distinguished militia members demonstrating exceptional skill;

(b) Thematic soldiers seeking professional careers;

(c) Foreign volunteers with proven military experience;

(d) Young men of any background who pass selection and complete training.

Article 21: Terms of Service

§1. Professional soldiers serve under the following terms:

(a) Initial enlistment for five years;

(b) Re-enlistment available indefinitely for those maintaining standards;

(c) Regular wages paid monthly, at rates competitive with mercenary service elsewhere;

(d) Provisions, equipment, and quarters provided;

(e) Share in plunder according to rank and contribution;

(f) Retirement benefits after twenty years: land grant or pension.

§2. Professional soldiers are subject to military law at all times, not merely when on campaign. Discipline is strict:

(a) Desertion: Death;

(b) Cowardice in battle: Death or degradation to labor units;

(c) Theft from comrades: Flogging and expulsion;

(d) Disobedience: Punishment according to severity, from extra duty to execution.

§3. Professional soldiers may not:

(a) Marry without permission of commanding officer;

(b) Engage in trade or commerce while in service;

(c) Hold other employment or obligation conflicting with military duty;

(d) Leave garrison or camp without authorization.

Article 22: The Officer Corps

§1. Command of all military forces—militia, pronoia, thematic, and professional—shall be exercised through a unified officer corps appointed by and answering to the Defensor Romaniae.

§2. Officers shall be selected based on:

(a) Demonstrated military competence;

(b) Leadership ability;

(c) Loyalty to the cause of restoration;

(d) Education in military science and history where available.

§3. Birth and wealth shall not be prerequisites for officer rank. A common soldier who demonstrates ability may rise to the highest commands. A noble who demonstrates incompetence shall not command.

§4. Officer ranks shall be:

(a) Dekarchos (Sergeant): Commands ten men;

(b) Kentarchos (Captain): Commands one hundred men;

(c) Taxiarchos (Major): Commands a battalion of 500-1000;

(d) Droungarios (Colonel): Commands a regiment of 2000-3000;

(e) Strategos (General): Commands a division or army corps;

(f) Megas Domestikos (Supreme Commander): Reserved for the Defensor Romaniae or his designated deputy.

§5. Officers are responsible for:

(a) Training the forces under their command;

(b) Maintaining discipline and equipment standards;

(c) Executing orders from superior authority;

(d) The welfare of their soldiers;

(e) Honest reporting of unit strength and capability.

§6. Officers who falsify reports, neglect training, abuse soldiers, or fail in their duties shall be removed and punished according to the severity of failure.

TITLE VI: THE NAVY

Article 23: Naval Forces

§1. The defense and restoration of the Empire require naval power. The Defensor Romaniae holds command over all naval forces as over land forces.

§2. Naval forces shall comprise:

(a) War Galleys (Dromones): For combat operations in coastal and restricted waters;

(b) Transport Ships (Ousiaka): For movement of troops and supplies;

(c) Fire Ships (Pyrophoroi): Equipped with Greek fire where available;

(d) Allied Vessels: Ships contributed by Venice, Genoa, Castile, or other allied powers operating under unified command.

§3. Crews shall be drawn from:

(a) Professional sailors in naval service;

(b) Militia levies from maritime guilds (shipwrights, fishermen, sailors);

(c) Coastal thematic populations in reconquered territories;

(d) Allied contributions.

Article 24: Maritime Obligations

§1. The guilds associated with maritime trades—shipwrights, rope makers, sailmakers, fishermen, and sailors—owe naval service in addition to or in place of wall militia service.

§2. Coastal settlements in reconquered territories shall owe naval rather than land thematic service, providing:

(a) Sailors proportional to population;

(b) Ships according to capacity;

(c) Harbor facilities and supplies for the fleet.

§3. Pronoia grants including harbor revenues or coastal properties carry naval obligations—provision of ships or sailors rather than cavalry.

TITLE VII: COMMAND AND CONTROL

Article 25: Unity of Command

§1. All military forces operating under this Charter answer to the Defensor Romaniae. There shall be no independent commands, private armies, or forces answering to other authority.

§2. When forces from allied nations serve alongside Roman forces:

(a) Overall strategic command rests with the Defensor Romaniae;

(b) Allied contingents retain their internal organization and immediate commanders;

(c) Coordination mechanisms shall be established before each campaign;

(d) Disputes over command shall be resolved by the Defensor or his designated deputy.

§3.** No regional governor, city official, or noble may command military forces except by delegation from the Defensor Romaniae. The old system of independent strategoi with regional military authority is abolished.

Article 26: Summons and Assembly

§1. When military need requires, the Defensor Romaniae issues summons specifying:

(a) Which forces are called (militia, pronoia, thematic, professional, or all);

(b) Where they shall assemble;

(c) When they must arrive;

(d) What equipment they must bring;

(e) Expected duration of service if known.

§2. Summons shall be communicated by:

(a) Written orders to military officers;

(b) Proclamation in public places;

(c) Church announcements;

(d) Beacon fires and bells for emergency mobilization.

§3. Response times:

(a) Constantinople militia: Two hours to assigned wall positions;

(b) Pronoia cavalry: Seven days to designated assembly point;

(c) Thematic forces: Fourteen days to designated assembly point;

(d) Professional forces: Immediate, as stationed.

§4. Failure to answer summons is punished as described in the relevant title of this Charter. Persistent failure constitutes desertion.

Article 27: Military Justice

§1. Military courts established by the Defensor Romaniae have jurisdiction over:

(a) All offenses committed by persons under arms;

(b) All offenses committed against military personnel, property, or operations;

(c) All failures of military obligation as defined in this Charter;

(d) All matters of military discipline.

§2. Military courts operate under procedures similar to the criminal procedures in the Charter of the Latin Courts, adapted for military necessity:

(a) The accused shall know the charges;

(b) The accused may speak in defense;

(c) Evidence shall be weighed fairly;

(d) Judgment shall be rendered promptly.

§3. In the field during active campaign, summary justice may be administered for offenses requiring immediate response (desertion in face of enemy, cowardice, mutiny), with review available after the campaign concludes.

TITLE VIII: SUPPLIES AND LOGISTICS

Article 28: Requisition Authority

§1. The Defensor Romaniae may requisition supplies, transport, and materials necessary for military operations, including:

(a) Grain, meat, wine, oil, and other provisions;

(b) Horses, mules, donkeys, and oxen;

(c) Wagons, carts, and boats;

(d) Timber, metal, leather, and other materials;

(e) Labor for military construction.

§2. Requisitions shall be:

(a) Proportional to need;

(b) Distributed fairly across the population;

(c) Compensated at fair rates from military funds;

(d) Documented and recorded.

§3. Abusive requisition—taking more than needed, targeting particular populations unfairly, failing to compensate—shall be punished as theft and abuse of authority.

Article 29: Military Treasury

§1. A military treasury, separate from civil revenues, shall fund the forces under this Charter. Sources include:

(a) Contributions under the Apokatastasis framework;

(b) Fines collected for military offenses and failures;

(c) Plunder from military operations (the Defensor's share);

(d) Tribute imposed on defeated enemies;

(e) Revenues from reconquered territories designated for military purposes;

(f) Contributions from allied powers;

(g) Such taxes as may be specifically designated for military use by imperial authority.

§2. The military treasury shall be administered by officers appointed by the Defensor Romaniae, with accounting rendered annually.

TITLE IX: RATIFICATION AND AMENDMENT

Article 30: Ratification

§1. This Charter takes effect upon:

(a) Acceptance by the Emperor of Constantinople, granting the title and authority of Defensor Romaniae; or

(b) Acceptance by a lawful assembly of the Roman people, should circumstances prevent imperial action.

§2. Until ratification, this Charter stands as a proposal and framework, to be refined as negotiations proceed.

Article 31: Amendment

§1. This Charter may be amended by agreement between the Defensor Romaniae and the Emperor, or their lawful successors.

§2. Amendments shall be published and proclaimed so that all affected persons may know their obligations.

CONCLUSIO

The salvation of the Roman Empire requires sacrifice from all its people. The farmer must become a soldier. The noble must lead from the front. The merchant must contribute treasure. The priest must bless the cause. There are no exemptions, no exceptions, no escapes.

But sacrifice shared is sacrifice honored. Those who give shall be remembered. Those who fight shall be rewarded. Those who fall shall be mourned as defenders of Christian civilization.

The choice belongs to Constantinople. Accept these obligations, and live. Reject them, and trust to fortune.

May God grant wisdom to those who choose, and strength to those who fight.

